{#- DEFINITION — plain-terms prose body -#}
<section class="sec reveal" id="qb-help-missing-transactions-definition" style="padding-top:24px;">
  <div class="ct read read--doc">
    <div class="eyebrow" style="margin-bottom:8px;">In plain terms</div>
    <h2 class="h2" style="margin-bottom:18px;">&ldquo;Missing transactions,&rdquo; plainly.</h2>
    <div class="prose">
      <p>A missing transaction is one you expect to see in QuickBooks that isn&rsquo;t showing up where you&rsquo;re looking. Usually that&rsquo;s one of a few places: a <em>report</em> that comes up short of what you know happened; a <em>register</em> with an obvious gap; or a <em>bank feed</em> that skipped a stretch of dates. The instinct is to assume the data is gone &mdash; but most of the time it isn&rsquo;t. A report date range or filter is hiding the transactions, they downloaded into a <em>different account</em> than you expected, or they&rsquo;re sitting unreviewed in the For Review tab and haven&rsquo;t been added to the books yet.</p>
      <p>The good news is that most of these trace to a short list of causes, and the self-fix steps below address them in order of likelihood &mdash; widening the date range and clearing filters surfaces a large share of &ldquo;missing&rdquo; transactions that were never actually gone. What the steps <em>can&rsquo;t</em> fix is a genuine gap: a bank-feed outage that never imported some dates, transactions that were accidentally deleted, or whole months that won&rsquo;t reconcile. That part is a ProAdvisor job, not a filter change. And if the underlying issue is an Intuit-side outage that skipped your dates, that&rsquo;s Intuit&rsquo;s to resolve &mdash; not something we can reach.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

